The paper discusses de-anonymization attacks on social networks, which are typically studied in the computer security (cs.CR) and social network analysis (cs.SI) sub-categories. The paper also analyzes the utility of anonymized data, which is related to database management (cs.DB) and cyber-physical systems (cs.CYBER). Finally, the paper evaluates state-of-the-art de-anonymization attacks on a real-world dataset, which falls under the social computing (cs.SOC) sub-category.
